comparanda

There are some parallels for the postures of the satyrs on this cup. For the silen on the back of the animals making a lewd gesture to Dionysos see Louvre G 88 (ARV2, 48, 162). For the scene of Dionysos standing in a chariot a good parallel is a neck amphora in Bologna (Bologna 29; ABV, 285, no. 3), where Dionysos and a woman are shown standing in the car of a frontal chariot, around which a silen and a nymph dance.

The pursuit of the Harpies by the Boreads appeared in Greek art as early as the 7th century, so even individual black-figure images of a bearded wind god are usually interpreted as a Boread, not as Boreas himself, whose iconography is poorly defined in this period (see LIMC, III, s.v. Boreadai
condit
Some gaps filled with plain clay. Moderate damage to some figures.
